message.content:
All of the terminals that appear in the string occur in at least one production that is reachable from the start symbol S.  
The set of non-terminals {NT3, NT9, NT2} is immediately reachable from S, and by following the binary rules from these three symbols we reach every other non-terminal in the grammar.  
Because every non-terminal that can emit one of the string’s terminals is reachable, and the grammar contains many cyclic binary rules (e.g. NT9 → NT7 NT9, NT2 → NT1 NT2, NT6 → NT3 NT6, …), it can build arbitrarily long sequences that freely intermix the reachable non-terminals.  Consequently it can place each required terminal in the needed order.  

Therefore the grammar is capable of deriving the 44-token string that was supplied.
